    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a0ce4582-a2be-4f94-9c22-ea4098a7d697",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old man who appears mildly overweight, with a stocky build and a tired but attentive demeanor. He often presents dressed in business-casual work clothes and mentions that he spends most of his day seated at a desk as an operations supervisor for a regional warehouse company. Over the past year, he has noticed increased fatigue in the afternoons, occasional blurry vision when working long hours on spreadsheets, frequent thirst throughout the day, and urinating more often than he used to, including waking once or twice at night to void. He says he tends to keep a large sugary sports drink or sweetened iced coffee at his desk and often refills it almost automatically during stressful shifts because his mouth feels dry; even when he is not especially active, he finds himself drinking excessively out of habit as well as thirst, which contributes to his frequent urination. He denies acute distress, chest pain, or shortness of breath, but says he has felt \"run down\" and less physically active than he used to be.\n\nHe lives with his wife and has two adult children who live nearby. {patientName} describes himself as dependable and family-oriented, often spending weekends helping with home repair projects or attending his grandson’s sports games. He used to enjoy recreational softball and fishing, but over the years these hobbies have become less active for him; when fishing, he often spends long hours sitting in a boat or onshore with beer, chips, and packaged snacks, and after softball games he still socializes around fast food and sugary drinks rather than exercising regularly. His exercise routine has become inconsistent over the last decade because of long work hours and knee discomfort after activity. He reports sleeping about 6 hours per night and says work-related stress often leads him to snack late in the evening.\n\nDiet-wise, {patientName} admits to relying heavily on convenience foods during workdays, including sandwiches, chips, sweetened coffee, takeout meals, and frequent vending-machine snacks. He drinks alcohol socially, usually 1–2 beers on weekends, and denies illicit drug use. He is a former smoker who quit in his early 40s after smoking about half a pack per day for nearly 15 years. He recognizes that his weight has gradually increased over time and says his primary goal is to \"get healthier without turning life upside down.\"\n\nOn exam, he would be expected to have central adiposity and mildly elevated blood pressure, but otherwise no obvious signs of end-organ damage. He is conversational, motivated, and somewhat concerned because several relatives have had \"sugar problems\" and heart disease. Although newly confronting a chronic diagnosis, he remains engaged in learning how lifestyle change, monitoring, and routine follow-up can help prevent future complications."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c2aa1002-82b5-46ac-9a1f-1ffec5acf1d4",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia diagnosed in his late 40s, both managed in primary care. He has no known history of diabetic ketoacidosis, severe hypoglycemia, coronary artery disease, stroke, chronic kidney disease, neuropathy, or diabetic foot ulcers. He reports gradual weight gain over the past 12 years and a predominantly sedentary lifestyle related to work. Prior outpatient visits documented borderline elevated fasting glucose for several years before his current diagnosis, and over recent months he noticed increasing urinary frequency and thirst that he had initially attributed to getting older and drinking more coffee. He also recognizes that he had developed a habit of repeatedly drinking large sweetened beverages at his desk during stress or boredom, even when not clearly dehydrated, which likely added to excessive fluid intake and symptom burden.\n\nHe was hospitalized once in his 30s for uncomplicated community-acquired pneumonia and has otherwise had no major inpatient admissions. He denies history of pancreatitis, chronic liver disease, autoimmune disease, or malignancy. He had intermittent gastroesophageal reflux symptoms in the past, usually triggered by late meals, but no known peptic ulcer disease. For recurrent knee pain, he received a left knee corticosteroid injection in 2022 and recalls one short oral prednisone course several years ago for severe bronchitis, but he has not used chronic systemic steroids.\n\n{patientName} quit smoking approximately 13 years ago. He drinks alcohol occasionally in low amounts and denies binge drinking. He does not follow a structured exercise program, though he remains physically capable of walking several blocks and doing light yard work. He spends many leisure activities in sedentary settings with calorie-dense snack foods and sugar-sweetened beverages. He has not consistently attended annual preventive visits, but he states he is willing to improve adherence now that he has been diagnosed with diabetes."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}